Reverts dotnet/roslyn#43235, which break ngen and might introduce runtime errors

@tmat @NTaylorMullen 
https://devdiv.visualstudio.com/DefaultCollection/DevDiv/_git/VS/pullrequest/244527

**Version Used**: 16.7.0 Preview 1.0 (30023.18)

**Steps to Reproduce**:

[SharpLab](https://sharplab.io/#v2:CYLg1APgxAdgrgGwQQwEYIKYAIMzZgWAChiABAJgEYyAGLUygFgG5iyBme8rAYSwG9iWYVgAOAJwCWAN2QAXbAwBs9SuwA8AeVQArDAGM5APiwBxXBnHyA9uIAUASiwBeE3IAW46wHcsMDL4ActZyAJIAtqKY4bgKwACiAB76GKJyktYwjqxEIlhCIqScyvSMWADK1jEekjAA5o4FwoK5eSIAZrYYyPrudrLiWJIK4UMwZhZWcraODk1tLW0iAL7zq0TLQA=)

```cs
#nullable enable

using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

public class C {
    private static IEnumerable<Object> Generator() => throw new NotImplementedException();
    
    public static void Something()
    {
        foreach (var item in Generator())
        {
        }
    }
}
```

In the VS editor, press Ctrl+. on the `var` keyword within the `foreach`. Execute the "Use explicit type instead of var" command.

**Expected Behavior**:

`object` replaces the `var` keyword.

**Actual Behavior**:

`object?` replaces the `var` keyword.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3548/80258904-98a27000-8641-11ea-91c1-94237468dbde.png)

While I get that Roslyn recently decided that implicit `var` types get nullable-annotations implicitly, in a `foreach` loop that makes no sense. The sequence being enumerated produces non-nullable items.  The C# does not allow for this variable to be assigned within the loop. Therefore it can *never* be null or assigned null. And therefore, should not carry the `?` annotation.

According to the [documentation](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/operators/null-forgiving), the null-forgiving operator has no effect at run time. However, it has a surprising side effect of breaking a [`null_conditional_operations`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/language-specification/expressions#null-conditional-operator) chain at compile time, which may change evaluation of the expression.  Consider this example:
```C#
int[] a = null;

// s1 is null: ToString() is not called at all
string s1 = a?.First().ToString();

// s2 is the empty string: ToString() is called on default(int?)
string s2 = a?.First()!.ToString();
```
Adding the `!` operator effectively changes parsing of the expression to `(a?.First())!.ToString()`.  Since this behavior is surprising for many developers (e.g., dotnet/docs#17988), I am wondering whether not allowing `!` in `null_conditional_operations` was due to omission rather than intentional design.  In the former case we might consider fixing this, in the latter — I would like to learn arguments that led to this decision.

